WHAT IS ACCESSIBILITY?

01

IMPORTANCE OF ACCESSIBILITY

Accessibility is a human right. It should be standard practice in adesign process - Not an after thought.

TYPES OF ACCESSIBILITY ISSUES

You should consider the number and types of potential accessibilityissues users will have. These are common barriers:

  • Visual impairment (e.g., variations of colour blindness,near/farsighted, etc.)
  • Motor/mobility (e.g., wheelchair-user concerns, motor skills)
  • Auditory (hearing difficulties, deafness)
  • Seizures (especially photosensitive epilepsy)
  • Learning/cognitive (e.g., dyslexia)

BUILDING ACCESSIBLE SITESBENEFITS EVERYONE:

  • Semantic HTML, which improves accessibility, also improves SEO,making your site more findable.
  • Caring about accessibility demonstrates good ethics and morals,which improves your public image. It shows inclusivity
  • makes your site more usable by other groups, such as mobilephone users or those on low network speed. Everyone can benefitfrom many such improvements.
  • is also legally required in some parts of the world.

UNFORTUNATELY...

  1. Accessibility is not achievable. However, we can do our best byfollowing the guidelines set by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
  2. s just not possible for 100% accessibility. For those who are hard ofhearing-- subtitles are not going to be accurate, especially if they're AI-generated. There have been improvements, yes but we have ways togo.

WORLD WIDE WEB CONSORTIUM(W3C®)

  • Created the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG)international standard.
  • Currently have produced WGAG 2.1 (with 2.2 in development)
  • https://www.w3.org/WAI/standards-guidelines/wcag/

4 PRINCIPLES OF WCAG

  • Perceivable: Users must be able to perceive it somehow, using one ormore of their senses.
  • Operable: Users must be able to control UI elements (e.g. buttons mustbe clickable in some way — mouse, keyboard, voice command, etc.).
  • Understandable: The content must be legible to its users.
  • Robust: The content must be developed using well-adopted webstandards that will work across different browsers, now and in the future.

  • This is an approach to design and development that aims to make pagesrender and function effectively on a variety of screen sizes and devices.
  • The goal is creating a consistent and user-friendly experience regardlessof no matter what device the user is accessing it from.

Although this approach originates in digital realms, it can also be workedwithin physical interactions, as seen in adaptive architecture,transformative furniture, responsive lighting, transportation, fashion, etc.

RESPONSIVE DESIGN:

RESPONSIVE DESIGN

By employing responsive design, you can achieve the following:

  • Expand your audience reach: In the present era, many users access theinternet using mobile devices.
  • Streamline development and save time: Designers and developers canconcentrate on a single design version, reducing time and effort.
  • Enhance SEO performance: Search engines offer improved search rankingsto mobile-friendly websites, boosting their visibility.
  • Maintain brand and design coherence across devices: Modifyingguidelines to fit various design frameworks is unnecessary, ensuringconsistent branding and design regardless of the device used.

POPULARITY OF RESPONSIVE DESIGN

During the early 2010s, designers faced a significant historical trend as a growingnumber of users began accessing web content on handheld devices rather thandesktop computers. To tackle this challenge, two primary design approachesemerged:

  • The adaptive design approach involved designers creating multiple versionsof a design, each optimized for specific devices with fixed dimensions.
  • The responsive design approach involved designers developing a single,flexible design that could adapt and adjust its layout to fit different screensizes, stretching or shrinking accordingly.

3 PRINCIPLES OF

RESPONSIVE DESIGN

  • Fluid Grid System
  • Fluid Images
  • Media Queries

FLUID GRID SYSTEMS

  • This image demonstrates that the fixed version of the content maintainsa consistent width regardless of the device, while the fluid version adaptsand occupies the available space based on the device's size.

FLUID IMAGES

  • Fluid images in responsive design areimages that automatically adjusttheir size to fit the container they areplaced in. This means that when thebrowser encounters a breakpoint,the image will either scale up or scaledown to match the current size ofthe window.

MEDIA QUERIES

Media queries serve as filters that identify the dimensions of the browsingdevice and ensure that your design adapts effectively to any screen size.To support media queries, breakpoints are utilized as specific valueswhere the content of your website is reorganized to offer users the mostoptimal browsing experience.

  • Commonly, designers usethree sizes when designingresponsive websites: 1024 &upwards, 1023-768, and767-320 px.

Responsive design involves designing with flexibility in mind for variouselements such as images, text, and layouts. To achieve this, you shouldconsider the following guidelines:

  • Embrace a "mobile-first" mindset: Whether you begin designing forthe smallest screen or the desktop version, adopting a mobile-firstmentality encourages a simplified design approach. This meansprioritizing content, reserving complex graphs and images for thedesktop version, and ensuring user-friendly tap targets for mobiledevices (with a minimum size of 30px).

PRACTICING RESPONSIVE DESIGN

PRACTICING RESPONSIVE DESIGN

PT. 2

  • Utilize Scalable Vector Graphics (SVGs): SVGs are a file format based onXML that supports 2D graphics, interactivity, and animations.
  • Implement three or more breakpoints: Designing for three or moredevices requires considering multiple screen sizes and adjusting the layoutaccordingly.
  • Prioritize and hide content based on user context: Evaluate thevisual hierarchy of your design, employ progressive disclosuretechniques, and utilize navigation drawers to present users with themost relevant information first. Less essential items should take asecondary role.
  • Strive for minimalism: Simplify your design by removing unnecessaryelements, focusing on essential features, and reducing clutter.

PRACTICING RESPONSIVE DESIGN

PT. 3

PRACTICING RESPONSIVE DESIGN

PT. 4

  • Apply design patterns to enhance user experience and familiarity:Implementing design patterns, such as the column drop pattern, allowscontent to adapt well to different screen types.
  • Ensure accessibility through font sizes and styles: Pay attention tolegibility by using appropriate font sizes and styles. Maintain effectivecontrast between text and background. Consider utilizing typographicscales to achieve harmony between body copy and headlines. Avoid usingtext within images to accommodate users who rely on screen readers.

03

Mobile UX pertains to the personal perception and satisfaction a userencounters while interacting with a mobile application.

UX designers are responsible for crafting a product that is delightful to useand offers a significant and fitting encounter for the user. In the realm ofmobile UX design, it is crucial to consider the entire customer journey,encompassing interactions, content, and sound design.

MOBILE DESIGN

02

  • today's mobile-centric world, this approach considers designing formobile devices first, as it can lead to more focused and efficientinterfaces. Developing for mobile devices first, before moving onto largerscreens, is based by the shift in behaviour and technological trends.
  • encourages designers and developers to prioritize the mobilecontent first experience and user interaction, leading to designs thatare more user-friendly and efficient digital products across all devices.

MOBILE-FIRST DESIGN:

MOBILE PRINCIPLES

There are several essential principles for mobile UX design:

  • Useful: The system should meet the users' needs and desires.
  • Usable: The system should be easy to use and understand.
  • Desirable: The design should evoke positive emotions and make userswant to use the system.
  • Findable: Users should be able to navigate easily and find importantinformation quickly.
  • Accessible: People with disabilities should be able to use the systemeffectively.
  • Credible: Users should trust the designer and the product.

Every screen you interact with in a digital product has multiple states to consider,

5 in fact:

  • Blank State: Also known as the empty state, is the initial or default state of the UI element orscreen before any content or data is displayed.
  • Loading State: This appears when the app fetches or processes data from a server orperforms a time-consuming task.informs the user that it is actively working and to waitfor the operation to complete.
  • Partial State: is used when only a portion of the content is available, displayed or loading in -a filtered data view is shown.
  • Error State: When something goes wrong, or an error is encountered during interactions ordata retrieval - communicating there's an issue.
  • Ideal State: Represents the intended, optimal, or successful state of a UI element or screenwhen everything is functioning as expected.

THE UI STACK

Desktop computers have a fixed horizontal orientation, which meansthe screen is wider than it is tall, and users can't change this.

On smartphones, the screen can be changed to either a vertical orhorizontal orientation. Most people (94%) use their smartphones in thevertical position, holding it upright, while a smaller percentage (6%)prefer the horizontal position, holding it sideways.

SCREEN ORIENTATION

ERGONOMICS

Ergonomics is the application of psychological and physiological principles to thedesign of products, processes, and systems. The goal of ergonomics is to reducehuman error, increase productivity, and enhance safety and comfort with a specificfocus on the interaction between the human and the thing of interest, whetherthat's a computer desk, stamping machine, or mobile phone.

  • The field is a combination of numerous disciplines, such as psychology, engineering,biomechanics, industrial design, physiology, interaction design, visual design, userexperience, and user interface design.

ERGONOMICS TYPES

There are several types of ergonomics:

  • Physical ergonomics - Designing interaction with equipment and workplaces(and playspaces) to fit the user.
  • Cognitive ergonomics - Designing products and services while keeping mentalprocesses, such as memory, reasoning, and decision-making in mind.
  • Organizational ergonomics - Design and optimization of business systems,including their organizational structures, policies, and processes.

SCREEN SIZE-DESIGNING

FOR THE THUMBS!

  • Placing important buttons and elements where the thumbcan reach them.
  • Using gestures for navigation to reduce the need to reachfor buttons.
  • Keeping the layout consistent across different screen sizes.
  • Avoid placing important buttons or elements at the top orbottom of the screen, as they are harder to reach with onethumb.
  • ensure that the mobile app or website is easy to use with one hand, designerscan use techniques such as:

MULTI-TOUCH INTERACTION PRINCIPLES

  1. Gesture-Based Interactions- Gestures are the primary means of interacting withmultitouch interfaces. These include taps, swipes, pinches, and other finger movements thatallow users to perform various actions.
  2. Direct Manipulation- This refers to the ability for users to directly manipulate objects onthe screen using their fingers. For example, users can directly zoom in and out on a map byusing the pinch gesture.
  3. Feedback-Feedback can come in the form of visual cues, such as highlighting an objectwhen it is touched, or haptic feedback, such as vibrations when a button is pressed.
  4. Simplicity- The more complex an interface is, the more difficult it is for users tounderstand and use. smaller screens and require users to perform actions with their fingers.It is essential that designers keep interfaces simple and easy to use.

GESTURES & SYMBOLS

  • Tap: The primary interaction method on mobile, equivalent to a click on a desktopdevice.
  • Double-tap: Two quick taps are often used for specific actions, like zooming in on mapsor liking posts in social media apps.
  • Swipe: Users touch the screen and move their fingers in a certain direction. Widely usedfor navigation, like scrolling or moving between screens.
  • Press, hold, drag: Users can reorder items in a list or move content around the interface.
  • Pinch (Zoom in/out): Users touch the screen with two fingers and move them closer orapart. Common for zooming in or out.
  • Long Press (Press and Hold): Holding down a tap for an extended period revealsadditional options or functions.
  • Pull Down (Refresh): Users drag content downwards to update or refresh the content.Common in social media or news apps.
  • https://www.uxpin.com/studio/blog/examples-of-interaction-design/

GESTURES EXPANDED

Desktop: People often use desktop computersfor important tasks like working in an office orshopping online.

Smartphone: Mobile phones offer morepersonalized features compared to desktops.

If you want your app to be accessible to userswherever they are, it's important to design it ina way that is easy to use outdoors. Use high-contrast colours in your app's design to makesure users can read everything, even if the sunis shining on their smartphones.

INPUT FIELDS

Input fields play a crucial role in user interface design as they allow users toinput information that may not always follow a standard format. You'veprobably encountered them when filling out your personal information andshipping address while shopping online or when submitting inquiries on theinternet. By allowing users to input specific and personalized details, thesefields can make interactions smoother and more efficient.

WHAT ARE FORM INPUT ATTRIBUTES?

Form input attributes create rules and context for users. These attributes also provide theappropriate controls–like displaying a numeric keypad on a mobile device for a phone number field.

Five essential HTML form input attributes UX designers must pay attention to:

  • Required: This attribute mandates that users fill out the input field before they can submit theform. It ensures essential information is provided.
  • Disabled: When an input is disabled, users cannot make any changes to it. This state is typicallyused when users need to complete another task before they can interact with the input field, orfor input fields that are meant for display purposes only.

WHAT ARE FORM INPUT ATTRIBUTES?

  • Type Attribute: The type attribute defines the format and behaviour of the input field. Forinstance, using the "password" type hides the characters entered for security, while the "email"type enforces the inclusion of the "@" symbol and a valid domain extension (e.g., ".com," ".co.uk,"etc.).
  • Label: Labels are crucial as they inform users about the purpose of the input field. They provideclear descriptions such as "Password," "Name," or "Email," helping users understand what isexpected of them.
  • Helper Text: Helper text serves as an additional label that offers context and enhancesaccessibility. It provides further information or instructions to guide users in filling out the inputfield correctly.

TYPES OF TYPES OF FORM INPUTS

Text inputs (or text input fields)allow designers to capture a widerange of information, most notablynames, emails, passwords,addresses, and other text-baseduser data.

TEXT INPUT

DATE PICKERS

Date pickers provide a format that makes it easy for users to select a day, month,and year. They also ensure that users use the correct separators like commas,backslashes, and dashes.

SELECTS/DROPDOWNS

Selects or dropdowns allow designers to present users with a collection of choices.Dropdowns work best for fixed variations or options–like a list of countries or t-shirtsizes. For long lists like countries or states, providing a search field allows users to findtheir choice quickly.

A checkbox performs two primary functions:

  • Allows users to make two or more selections
  • Provides a method to acknowledge legal requirements–like accepting terms andconditions or email newsletter opt-ins

CHECKBOXES

Radio buttons perform a similar function to checkboxes but only allow one choiceinstead of multiple. For example, choosing a shipping option or answering yes/noquestions.

RADIO BUTTONS

Toggles or toggle switches are basic on/off (boolean) form inputs. Switches offer usersa quick method for making yes/no, on/off decisions. If you’re looking for an example,both Android and iOS mobile devices use toggle switches in their settings.

TOGGLES/SWITCHES

File inputs allow users to upload images and documents. UX designers must use helpertext to tell users which format the file input will accept, i.e., PNG, JPG, PDF, etc.

FILE INPUT

Forms/input field types are not limited to just one category. For efficiency andinformation gathering, designers will often include multiple types, depending oncontext.

USING A COMBINATION OF INPUTS

  • Inactive: input where the user has entered information
  • Focused: highlighted to show the user’s current selection
  • Activated: completed input
  • Hover: shows desktop users that this is an interactive input when theymove their cursor over it
  • Error: alerts the user to a problem–i.e., an incomplete field or incorrectinformation
  • Disabled: tells the user they can’t interact with the input

INPUT STATES

These states help designers convey information to users and indicate howelements respond to user interactions.

BEST PRACTICES FOR INPUT FIELDS

  1. Use short, descriptive input labels-Input labels must be short, descriptive, and fully visible. Thisexample from Material Design shows how long labels can confuse users
  2. Use an appropriate colour contrast-Form inputs are not the place for branding or creativecolour schemes. Choose a background colour that contrasts nicely with the placeholder and inputtext.
  3. Convey input requirements-Passwords can cause confusion and frustration if UX designersdon’t tell users the field’s requirements.
  4. Distinguish between required and optional-Telling users which fields are required and optionalcan reduce errors while allowing people to choose what they want to share. The standard practice isto add an asterisk (*) for required fields, but many designers place (required) in brackets next toform labels to be more explicit and help with accessibility.

BEST PRACTICES FOR INPUT FIELDS

  1. Put placeholder text -The placeholder text gives the user an idea of what goes in the input field. Itshouldn't provide instructions. That's because, once you start typing, the instructions disappear.
  2. Structure inputs to reduce thinking-Structured inputs tell users exactly what data and format areneeded. It also reduces thinking to complete forms faster.
  3. Enable autocomplete-Autocomplete (autofill) allows users to complete forms much faster, especiallyfor addresses–like using the Google Maps API to find an address.
  4. Use default values with caution-Default values offer similar benefits to autocomplete, allowing users tocomplete forms faster. However, default could result in errors or confusion. For example, location tracking toset a default value for a user’s country might be incorrect if they’re away from home or using a VPN
  5. Design mobile-friendly input fields-Mobile-friendly or responsive designcrucial for good form UX.Designers must use one-column layouts and optimize all form elements for touch/tap interactions.

APP INTERACTIONS

  • App interactions refer to the ways a user can engage with and manipulate thecontent of features within an interaction. This action is central to the user’sexperience and can vary widely based on the purpose and design - some of theseinteractions can also be found when interacting with physical objects.

Some of the common interactions include:

  • Navigation, Scrolling, Tapping, Swiping andGestures, Drag-and-Drop, Input Forms,Sliders and Adjustments, Search,Notifications, Multitouch and MultiscreenInteractions, Augmented Reality (AR), Voiceto Speech, Payment and Transactions,Sharing and Socials, or Gaming Interactions.
